article.description: Lauren Jackson had 23 points and Felicia Ragland added 19 points, six assists and three steals in her first start to lead the Seattle Storm to a 90-82 victory over Phoenix on Friday night, snapping the Mercury's four-game winning streak.

related.description: Phoenix Mercury coach Cynthia Cooper left before Friday's game with the Seattle Storm as her twins were set to be born by a surrogate mother in Houston.
related.linkText: Cooper leaves Mercury for birth of surrogate twins
related.title: Cooper leaves team for children's birth
related.headline: Cooper leaves team for children's birth

article.headline: Jackson, Ragland send Storm past Mercury
article.linkText: Jackson, rookie Ragland lead Storm past Mercury
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Lauren Jackson had 23 points and Felicia Ragland added 19 points, six assists and three steals in her first start to lead the Seattle Storm to a 90-82 victory over Phoenix on Friday night, snapping the Mercury's four-game winning streak.

Phoenix coach Cynthia Cooper left the team before the game to go
to Houston, where a surrogate mother was set to give birth to
Cooper's twins. Assistant coach Linda Sharp, the former coach of
the Los Angeles Sparks, ran the team in Cooper's absence.

Ragland, who had scored seven points in four games and none in
the last two, was 7-of-11 from the field, including 3-of-5 from
beyond the 3-point line.

"I went out there and just played my game,'' Ragland said.

Ragland had two fastbreak layups in the first two minutes as
Seattle (4-3) took a 13-4 lead by taking advantage of four Mercury
turnovers in the first five minutes.

"What we liked about Ragland is her ability to get out and run and put pressure on the defense,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn of the second-round draft pick from Oregon State.

Phoenix (4-2), which fell behind by as many as 17 points on
Thursday night before coming back to beat Detroit, trailed by as
many as 19 against Seattle and never got closer than four in the
second half.

"I do not know what it is about us starting off slow,'' said
Jennifer Gillom, who led the Mercury with 25 points. "We can't
keep trying to be a second-half team because we are not that
good.''

Adriana Moises hit a 3-pointer and then made two free throws
with 47 seconds left to cut the lead to 86-82.

Sue Bird made two free throws with 38 seconds left and Phoenix's
Gillom missed a 3-pointer with 20 seconds to go. Semeka Randall
added two more free throws with 18 seconds left.

Gillom had 11 points during a stretch early in the second half
as the Mercury cut the lead to 52-44.

Bird, the Storm's leading scorer and the league's No. 1 overall
draft pick, was held to 14 points, three under her average. Kamila
Vodichkova added 11 points and nine rebounds for Seattle.

Moises had 20 points and Lisa Harrison added 16 for the Mercury.
